The OSI Model is a 7-layer networking model used to understand how data travels from one computer to another over a network.
It was developed by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO).

7 Layers of OSI Model
         Sender 
Key Sender-Side Process (Top-Down):
Layer 7 - Application: Generates data (e.g., HTTP request).
Layer 6 - Presentation: Encrypts, compresses, or formats data.
Layer 5 - Session: Opens and manages the connection.
Layer 4 - Transport: Segments data; adds source/destination ports (TCP/UDP).
Layer 3 - Network: Adds logical IP addresses; packages data into packets.
Layer 2 - Data Link: Adds physical MAC addresses; frames data.
Layer 1 - Physical: Converts frames into binary bits (0s and 1s) and transmits via physical media


Data Encapsulation and De-Encapsulation
Data Encapsulation
When data travels from sender to receiver, each layer adds a header to the data.
This process is called Data Encapsulation.
Data Decapsulation
At the receiver side, each layer removes the header added by the sender.
This process is called Data Decapsulation.

Flow:
Application → Presentation → Session → Transport → Network → Data Link → Physical


Application Layer
	Provides interface between user and network applications
	Allows applications to communicate over the network.
Ex.
	Web browsers
	Email clients
	File transfer applications
Presentation Layer
Responsible for data formatting and security.
Functions:
  Encryption / Decryption
Converting readable data to unreadable data for security.
Example:
Plain text → Encrypted text
   Encoding / Decoding
Converting one data format to another.
Example:
ASCII → EBCDIC
   Compression / Decompression
	Reduces size of data for faster transmission
	Restores data back to original size at receiver.

Session Layer
Responsible for connection management between devices.
Functions:
	Establish session
	Maintain session
	Terminate session

Dialogue Control :Dialogue Control is used to control the communication between two devices, meaning it decides how the devices will send and receive data during a session.
Communication types:
Simplex
	One-way communication
	Example: TV broadcasting, Radio
Half Duplex
	Two-way communication but one device at a time
       Example: Walkie-talkie
Full Duplex
	Two-way communication simultaneously
       Example: Mobile phone call

Transport Layer
Responsible for end-to-end communication.
Functions:
Port Addressing
Assigns source and destination port numbers.
Example:
	HTTP → Port 80
	HTTPS → Port 443
	SSH → Port 22
Segmentation
Large data is divided into small segments.
Flow Control
Controls data transmission speed according to receiver capacity.

TCP and UDP
TCP (transmission control protocol) – connection oriented – transmitter receives acknowledgement for all the messages transmitted by transmitter.
UDP (user datagram protocol - connection less) – there will not be any acknowledgements.

Network Layer
Responsible for logical addressing and routing.
Functions:
IP Addressing
Assigns source and destination IP addresses.
Example:
192.168.1.10 → 8.8.8.8
Fragmentation
Large packets are divided into smaller fragments.
Routing
Finding the best path to transfer data between networks.
Devices used: Routers

Data Link Layer
Responsible for node-to-node communication.
Functions:
Physical Addressing
Assigns MAC addresses.

Example MAC address:
00:1A:2B:3C:4D:5E
Error Detection and Correction
Detects and corrects transmission errors.
Devices: Switch , Bridge

Physical Layer
Responsible for actual transmission of data through cables or wireless signals.
Functions:
	Converts data into bits (0s and 1s)
	Handles electrical signals
Devices: Hub ,Cables, Repeaters

Always explain layer-wise debugging: 
	L1 → Interface 
	L3 → IP & routing 
	L4 → Port 
	L7 → Application (curl) 
Mention tools
	tcpdump → packet level 
	ss → socket level 
	curl → application level



